{"word": "-겠-", "pos": "suffix", "senses": [{"examples": [{"text": "다시는 담배를 피우지 않겠다!", "bold_text_offsets": [[13, 14]], "roman": "dasi-neun dambae-reul piuji anketda!", "bold_roman_offsets": [[30, 33]], "translation": "I won't smoke again!", "english": "I won't smoke again!", "type": "example"}, {"text": "철수가 오늘 김밥을 먹겠대요.", "bold_text_offsets": [[12, 13]], "roman": "Cheolsu-ga oneul gimbab-eul meokgetdaeyo.", "bold_roman_offsets": [[32, 35]], "translation": "Cheolsu said he would eat kimbap today.", "english": "Cheolsu said he would eat kimbap today.", "type": "example"}], "links": [["speculative", "speculative#English"], ["-으시-", "-으시-#Korean"], ["will", "will"], ["intend", "intend"]], "raw_glosses": ["A general future speculative suffix; it attaches directly to the stem, including the honorific -으시- (-eusi-), and precedes another verbal suffix.", "(mainly used with 1st person or in quotative sentences) will, intend: a suffix indicating that the subject intends to do the action in the future with their own efforts, thus showing their will, determination."], "glosses": ["A general future speculative suffix; it attaches directly to the stem, including the honorific -으시- (-eusi-), and precedes another verbal suffix.", "will, intend: a suffix indicating that the subject intends to do the action in the future with their own efforts, thus showing their will, determination."], "categories": ["Korean terms with usage examples"], "tags": ["mainly", "morpheme"], "raw_tags": ["used with 1st person or in quotative sentences"]}, {"examples": [{"text": "내일 비가 오겠네요.", "bold_text_offsets": [[7, 8]], "roman": "Naeil bi-ga ogen-ne-yo.", "bold_roman_offsets": [[13, 16]], "translation": "Tomorrow it will probably rain.", "english": "Tomorrow it will probably rain.", "type": "example"}, {"text": "어제 모스크바에서도 눈이 내렸겠지요?", "bold_text_offsets": [[16, 17]], "roman": "eoje Moseukeuba-eseo-do nun-i naeryeotget-ji-yo?", "bold_roman_offsets": [[38, 41]], "translation": "It probably snowed in Moscow too yesterday, right?", "english": "It probably snowed in Moscow too yesterday, right?", "type": "example"}], "links": [["speculative", "speculative#English"], ["-으시-", "-으시-#Korean"], ["will", "will"], ["may", "may"]], "glosses": ["A general future speculative suffix; it attaches directly to the stem, including the honorific -으시- (-eusi-), and precedes another verbal suffix.", "will, may: A suffix denoting guess or assumption of varied possibility."], "categories": ["Korean terms with usage examples"], "tags": ["morpheme"]}, {"examples": [{"text": "제가 말을 좀 해도 되겠어요?", "bold_text_offsets": [[12, 13]], "roman": "je-ga mar-eul jom hae-do doegesseoyo?", "bold_roman_offsets": [[28, 31]], "translation": "Would it be okay if I said something?", "english": "Would it be okay if I said something?", "type": "example"}], "links": [["speculative", "speculative#English"], ["-으시-", "-으시-#Korean"], ["will", "will"], ["would", "would"]], "glosses": ["A general future speculative suffix; it attaches directly to the stem, including the honorific -으시- (-eusi-), and precedes another verbal suffix.", "will, would: A suffix indicating an indirect polite proposal with some degree of future supposition."], "categories": ["Korean terms with usage examples"], "tags": ["morpheme"]}], "head_templates": [{"name": "ko-suffix", "args": {}, "expansion": "-겠- • (-get-)"}], "categories": ["Korean entries with incorrect language header", "Korean lemmas", "Korean suffixes", "Korean terms derived from Middle Korean", "Korean terms inherited from Middle Korean", "Korean terms with redundant script codes", "Korean terms with redundant transliterations", "Korean terms without ko-IPA template", "Pages with 1 entry", "Pages with entries"], "forms": [{"form": "-get-", "tags": ["romanization"]}, {"form": "-게엿-", "tags": ["alternative", "Early", "Modern"], "roman": "-geyeot-"}, {"form": "-게얏-", "tags": ["alternative", "Early", "Modern"], "roman": "-geyat-"}, {"form": "-갯-", "tags": ["alternative", "Hamgyong"], "roman": "-gaet-"}, {"form": "-겄-", "tags": ["alternative"], "roman": "-geot-"}, {"form": "-갔-", "tags": ["alternative"], "roman": "-gat-"}, {"form": "-갓-", "tags": ["alternative"], "roman": "-gat-"}], "related": [{"tags": ["adnominal", "irrealis", "suffix"], "roman": "-eul", "word": "-을"}], "etymology_number": 1, "etymology_text": "Contraction of older and synonymous 게 하였 (-ge ha-yeot-), 게 ᄒᆞ엿 (Yale: -key hoy-es-) in historical spelling. 게 ᄒᆞ엿 (Yale: -key hoy-es-) has been used with future meaning since the late sixteenth century.\nIn Modern Korean, 게 하였 (-ge ha-yeot-) most literally means \"caused [one] to [VERB]\", e.g. 먹게 하였다 (meok-ge ha-yeot--da, “[I] made [him] eat”). Hence, there are multiple theories with regards to the semantics. Some believe that the verb 하다 (hada) in this context was synonymous to 되다 (doeda), and hence that the construction originally had the same meaning as modern 게 되었 (-ge doe-eot-), e.g. 먹게 되었다 (meok-ge doe-eot--da, “[he] ended up eating”). Others believe that the suffix developed from a more reflexive use of the causative, equivalent to modern 도록 하였 (-dorok ha-yeot-), e.g. 먹도록 하였다 (meok-dorok ha-yeot--da, “[he] decided to eat”).\nIncreasingly displaced older future-like -으리- (-euri-).", "etymology_templates": [{"name": "okm-l", "args": {"1": "게 ᄒᆞ엿", "2": "-key hoy-es-"}, "expansion": "게 ᄒᆞ엿 (Yale: -key hoy-es-)"}, {"name": "okm-l", "args": {"1": "게 ᄒᆞ엿", "2": "-key hoy-es-"}, "expansion": "게 ᄒᆞ엿 (Yale: -key hoy-es-)"}], "lang": "Korean", "lang_code": "ko"}
